title: Okay, so far I like Version #4 of the concept photos
body:
This version with the jewelry, them eating fruit/grapes gave me A LOT of “Blood Sweat & Tears” vibes.

BS&T and WINGS in general used a lot of Baroque/18th Century elements to represent “falling into temptation” or corruption of innocence and entering adulthood.

Map Of The Soul: PERSONA seems to still be using those same elements but with late 19th-mid 20th century (VERY SUBTLE) elements mixed with modern (Modern Renaissance to be exact) to represent the many masks that we, as individuals, wear on a daily basis. As if reminding us that even in modern times we’re all still actors in a play creating a “Persona” to deal with the world around us because deep down we’re afraid to show who we really are and risk being judged on it.

And I really like how Bangtan as executing the concept through the photos to show the lives of Idols/public figures/entertainers.

Sometimes all we see is the glamour, the bright lights, the expensive clothing, the jewelry, the “happy smiles”, and flashy choreography. But as fans, we may never really get to see who these people are “in real life”; all the struggles, pain, tears and frustrations that they’re going through. Even IF they willingly show it to us it’ll be “toned down” to prevent shocking the fans to the point of feeling excessive pity, anger or some other type of emotion that may prevent us from supporting them AS FANS.

So… yeah, I like it so far.
